        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/whatnoww/{size}/54328_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-04-11T09:09:47.856Z",
        "cooked": "<p>The simple solution would be: You would still need to be discoverable in this case, it’s just that the other client would have to pretend to not see you XD. I don’t think Signal would be willing to implement a security feature that is so easily “workaroundable” at a technical level.</p>\n<p>A more complicated solution would be:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>First of all, you would need to send your phone number and PNI to an authenticated endpoint with no server delivery receipts preferably requesting a specific number.</li>\n<li>Server would need to silently deliver the message to the other device.</li>\n<li>Your device would have to wait for the other device to send you an unauthenticated message back revealing their PNI, and revealing their registered.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Hmmm, actually, on second thought it doesn’t sound that bad. The main drawback is that you could potentially end up waiting a really long time for that other device to wake up and respond to your message request and the ambiguity on who’s actually registered or if you’re just waiting for a response.</p>",
